## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

**10 tests, 0 real verifications.** This is a systematic **coverage-touching** test class. Every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called (hitting 95% coverage), but almost nothing is actually verified. These tests will pass even if every method is completely broken — as long as it doesn't throw.

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| Critical | 7 |
| High | 1 |
| Medium | 2 |
| Low | 0 |

---

### Critical Findings

#### 1. Coverage Touching (Systemic — all 10 tests)

The entire class is a coverage-touching pattern. Methods are called in near-declaration order with no meaningful assertions. This is *why* you have 95% coverage but production bugs.

#### 2. No Assertions — `AddProduct_Works` (line 17–21)

Calls `AddProduct` but never verifies the product was stored.

**Fix:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void AddProduct_StoresProduct()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);
    var stored = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.AreEqual("Widget", stored?.Name);
    Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, stored?.Price);
}
```

#### 3. No Assertions — `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 31–36)

Calls `UpdatePrice` but never checks the price actually changed. A bug in the `Save(p with { Price = newPrice })` logic would go undetected.

**Fix:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void UpdatePrice_ChangesPriceOfExistingProduct()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    _catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
    var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated?.Price);
}
```

#### 4. No Assertions — `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 38–43)

Never checks the product is actually gone after removal.

**Fix:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void RemoveProduct_MakesProductUnfindable()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    _catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.IsNull(_catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
}
```

#### 5. No Assertions — `GetProductCount_Works` (line 63–66)

Calls `GetProductCount()`, discards the result. Doesn't even have a trivial `IsNotNull`.

**Fix:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetProductCount_ReturnsNumberOfStoredProducts()
{
    Assert.AreEqual(0, _catalog.GetProductCount());
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    Assert.AreEqual(1, _catalog.GetProductCount());
}
```

#### 6. No Assertions — `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (line 68–74)

